---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'What to Do After Workplace Harassment | SexualHarassmentCalc';
const description = 'Practical, ordered steps after a workplace sexual harassment incident: documentation, evidence preservation, internal complaint, EEOC filing, attorney consultation, retaliation protections, and severance traps.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>What to Do After Workplace Harassment</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by our editorial team. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>
    The hours and days after a workplace sexual harassment incident are when the most consequential decisions get made &mdash;
    usually badly, because the people making them are exhausted, scared, or being rushed by an HR department that does not work
    for them. This guide is a practical, ordered playbook. It is not legal advice for your specific situation; talk to an
    employment plaintiff&rsquo;s attorney before any deadline passes.
  </p>

  <h2>1. Make yourself safe</h2>
  <p>
    If the conduct was a physical assault or a credible threat, your first call is to law enforcement, not HR. A criminal report
    creates a contemporaneous record that strengthens any later civil claim. If you need medical care, get it; if you need a
    sexual-assault forensic exam, hospitals provide it free in most states under the Violence Against Women Act funding structure.
    Document the time, the location, and the personnel who treated you.
  </p>

  <h2>2. Document everything, contemporaneously</h2>
  <p>
    The single biggest predictor of case value, holding facts constant, is the quality of contemporaneous documentation. Start a
    private journal &mdash; not on a work device, not in a work email, not in a work-issued cloud account. Write down:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Date, time, and location of each incident.</li>
    <li>Exactly what was said or done, in quoted form where possible.</li>
    <li>Who else was present or within hearing distance.</li>
    <li>Your immediate response.</li>
    <li>How the incident affected your work that day or after (missed meetings, sleep, anxiety symptoms).</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Update the journal the same day if at all possible. Contemporaneous notes are admissible under various exceptions to the hearsay
    rule and carry substantially more weight than reconstructions written months later.
  </p>

  <h2>3. Preserve evidence the employer might delete</h2>
  <p>
    Save copies of relevant texts, emails, Slack/Teams messages, voicemails, photos, and access logs to a personal device or
    personal cloud account. Use your own device&rsquo;s camera to photograph computer screens if a system will not let you forward.
    Do not delete anything yourself, even if it embarrasses you &mdash; deletion is its own evidentiary problem (spoliation), and
    a lawyer will want to see the whole record.
  </p>
  <p>
    Specifically preserve:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Direct messages from the harasser.</li>
    <li>Emails about scheduling, performance reviews, or assignments that changed after the conduct began.</li>
    <li>Your own performance reviews, raises, bonuses, and any HR write-ups before and after the conduct.</li>
    <li>The employer&rsquo;s anti-harassment policy, employee handbook, and training materials.</li>
    <li>Any text or message from a coworker who witnessed something or to whom you described it.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>4. File an internal complaint, in writing</h2>
  <p>
    There is no federal requirement to use HR before filing an EEOC charge, but failure to use a reasonable internal complaint
    procedure can support the employer&rsquo;s <em>Faragher</em>/<em>Ellerth</em> affirmative defense in supervisor
    hostile-environment cases without tangible action. So: file the internal complaint in writing, route it to the person the
    policy designates (not the harasser&rsquo;s direct supervisor if that&rsquo;s the same person), keep a date-stamped copy on
    a personal device, and follow up in writing if the company does not respond in a reasonable time.
  </p>
  <p>
    Keep the complaint factual: dates, times, conduct, witnesses. Avoid editorializing or legal conclusions (do not call it
    &ldquo;sexual harassment under Title VII&rdquo;); the legal characterization is for your lawyer, not your HR file.
  </p>

  <h2>5. Consult an employment plaintiff&rsquo;s attorney</h2>
  <p>
    Before the EEOC deadline. Most employment plaintiff&rsquo;s firms offer free initial consultations on harassment matters and
    work on contingency, so there is no out-of-pocket cost to find out whether your case is viable. The intake will cover claim
    theories, available statutes (federal versus state), the realistic damages structure, the statute of limitations, and the
    employer&rsquo;s likely defenses. Bring the timeline, the documents, and a list of witnesses.
  </p>
  <p>
    Three free or low-cost places to find a plaintiff-side attorney: NELA (National Employment Lawyers Association) member
    directory; your state bar&rsquo;s lawyer-referral service; legal-aid organizations for low-income workers (often have
    employment units).
  </p>

  <h2>6. File an EEOC charge or state-agency complaint before the deadline</h2>
  <p>
    The federal deadline is <strong>180 days</strong> from the last act of harassment, extended to <strong>300 days</strong> in
    states with a fair-employment agency (most states). California, New York, New Jersey, and others have longer state-agency
    windows (3 years in CA and NY for sexual harassment specifically). Federal-sector employees have 45 days to contact an EEO
    counselor &mdash; far shorter than the private-sector window.
  </p>
  <p>
    Missing a federal deadline ends the federal claim. Continuing-violation doctrine
    (<em>Nat&rsquo;l R.R. Passenger Corp. v. Morgan</em>, 536 U.S. 101 (2002)) sometimes pulls older incidents into a timely
    charge in hostile-environment cases, but do not rely on it without a lawyer&rsquo;s confirmation.
  </p>

  <h2>7. Understand your retaliation protection</h2>
  <p>
    From the moment you file an internal complaint or an EEOC charge, you are protected from retaliation under
    42 U.S.C. &sect; 2000e-3(a) and parallel state provisions. Retaliation can include termination, demotion, schedule changes,
    exclusion from meetings, undeserved negative reviews, transfers, shunning, and threats. Document any change in treatment
    after your complaint as carefully as you documented the underlying conduct. Retaliation claims are often the strongest part
    of a case, because temporal proximity between complaint and adverse action is usually easy to prove.
  </p>

  <h2>8. Be careful with severance offers</h2>
  <p>
    If the employer offers severance after a complaint, do not sign without an employment lawyer reviewing it. Standard severance
    agreements include a general release of all employment-related claims, including the harassment and retaliation claims you
    just raised. Once signed it is very difficult to undo. Employees 40 or older have a 21-day consideration window and a 7-day
    revocation window for ADEA waivers under the Older Workers Benefit Protection Act; many employers extend those windows for
    other claims as well. Use the time. A lawyer can often negotiate the severance number up materially when there is a credible
    harassment claim attached.
  </p>
  <p>
    Two specific terms to scrutinize:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Confidentiality / non-disparagement.</strong> Post-Speak Out Act 2022, pre-dispute NDAs covering harassment are unenforceable. Many states (CA, NY, NJ, IL) also limit post-dispute NDAs covering the underlying conduct. The dollar amount can be confidential; the facts increasingly cannot.</li>
    <li><strong>No-rehire / forfeiture.</strong> Some severance agreements include forfeiture-of-vested-benefits triggers tied to filing future claims. These can be unenforceable in some jurisdictions, but they are worth a lawyer&rsquo;s eyes before you sign.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>9. Take care of your mental health</h2>
  <p>
    A harassment case is emotionally exhausting, and the litigation timeline runs 12 to 36 months from charge to settlement.
    Treating-provider records (therapist, primary care, psychiatrist) document the emotional-distress harm and substantially
    increase the compensatory-damages component. They also help you. If your insurance covers mental-health care, use it.
  </p>

  <h2>10. Manage your social media</h2>
  <p>
    Defense counsel will subpoena social media. Do not delete posts after the incident &mdash; that is spoliation. Do tighten
    privacy settings, stop posting about the case, the employer, the harasser, the lawsuit, your symptoms, or your treatment.
    Talk to your lawyer about social media before you do anything substantive online.
  </p>

  <h2>What this guide is not</h2>
  <p>
    It is not legal advice for your specific situation. The general sequence above fits most fact patterns, but the right
    sequencing for <em>your</em> case depends on facts, jurisdiction, employer size, evidence, and timing that only a licensed
    attorney can evaluate. Talk to one before any statute of limitations passes.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
